@Steve L

I learned about the British meaning of a college on our UK trip, when we visited Cambridge, among other places.

Also, all Polish insitutions of higher learning are expected to engage in research, except for "państwowa wyższa szkoła zawodowa", the equivalent of your vocational schools, but on a level above high schools. The quality of the research determines many things: among others, how much money the institution gets from the goverment, and what it may be called: only the best schools may be called "Uniwersytet". Less prestigious schools are called "Akademia". Some of our best schools who qualify for the university designation choose to be recognized by their historical names though. For example, Warsaw's best and oldest economic university is known as Szkoła Główna Handlowa (literally, the Main School of Trade).

